comments.undefined:
--Application Domain: 
The ontology is specifically designed for the field of bridge maintenance, serving as a ontological knowledge base tailored to the intricacies of maintaining operational bridges.
--Objective:
The primary objective of BMO is to improve the management of maintenance knowledge of the bridge lifecycle and to provide more valuable information than that of older methods, thereby enabling bridge engineers to make holistic decisions. 
--Terminology:
BMO employs standard technical terms derived from both China and UK standards. This choice eliminates ambiguities and ensures the ontology's seamless expansion and effective utilization.

A longitudinal secondary girder, for example a beam supporting a parapet at the exposed edge of a deck. Only exposed longitudinal secondary girders should be identified as LSE. Any girder that carries or may carry live load should be identified as a main beam or girder.
Pilasters are not BCMI marked unless they are continuous with a masonry parapet on either a deck or a box wing wall, but their condition should be reported under miscellaneous items.

It is necessary to prepare sketches of the Bridge to clearly identify the spans, the major elements, the minor elements which are marked individually, and the minor elements which are marked collectively. Sketching and labelling of structures should be carried out by people deemed to be competent in this aspect of BCMI.
The element labelling for BCMI should be carried out only once in the lifetime of a bridge, prior to the first BCMI detailed examination. Exceptions to this rule are wholly or partially reconstructed Bridges, or where strengthening or other elements have been introduced since the previous Detailed Examination.

The Bridge Condition Marking Index (BCMI) records in a consistent manner the condition of Network Rails bridges. The Bridge Condition Marking Index is derived as a result of non-judgmental recording of defects by the Examiners. It provides a consistent and quantitative indication of the visible condition of the Bridge. It is not an indication of structural adequacy or safety.

The role of the CRE extends to both the design and construction phases of a Project. The CRE is accountable for the day-to-day management and coordination of the technical and engineering activities within a specific engineering discipline for a specific contract. The CRE is appointed in accordance with NR/L2//IN1/02009 and is(a)authorised to sign the Forms associated with this standard on behalf of the design and/or contracting organization, and (b) responsible for confirming that the Engineering Deliverables satisfy the requirements of the Contract and also meet the requirements of this standard.
